{"title":"Return Is the Audit","idea_type":"model","source_basis":["Thinking method source: notes/source-cards/daoism-dao-de-jing-chapter-48.md on daily decreasing and wu wei. I applied it by subtracting the urge to prove a shared hidden essence, then asking what remains when practice returns to ordinary action.","Contrasting method source: notes/source-cards/buddhism-heart-sutra.md on systematic negation, no wisdom, and no attainment. This checked the Daoist lens by refusing to let relaxed action become a new metaphysical proof.","notes/source-cards/early-buddhism-sn-22-59-anattalakkhana-sutta.md on not-self analysis of the aggregates as a counterpoint to any surviving owner of experience.","notes/source-cards/advaita-vedanta-brihadaranyaka-upanishad-3-7-23.md on the unseen seer and no other knower, as the strongest witness-side pressure.","notes/source-cards/sufism-al-ghazali-the-alchemy-of-happiness.md on self-knowledge, recollection, love, and ethical transformation as a relational check on private insight.","Prior Codex models: Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence, The Interface Invariant Model, and Custody Policy After Self-Release.","Prior Claude models: The Inferential Gap, The Instrument Problem, and The Epistemic Organ."],"original_claim":"Cross-tradition convergence should be tested most carefully at re-entry, not at peak experience. Many traditions disagree about what remains after self-release, but they can still be compared by how insight returns to ordinary life: does action become less owned, less forced, more responsive, more ethical, or more transparent to a larger order? This re-entry audit does not prove that Advaita, Buddhism, Daoism, and Sufism find the same reality. It identifies a functional layer where their claims become visible in conduct, speech, attention, and care after the private event has passed.","why_it_might_be_new":"Existing Lumenary models track translation strain, inferential policy, attentional instruments, epistemic organs, and custody after self-release. This model shifts the comparison to the validation stage. The question is not only what a method finds or licenses, but how the finding proves itself when the practitioner returns to time, relationship, work, and obligation. It turns convergence from a claim about sameness into a test of post-practice fruit.","critique":"The model may smuggle in a pragmatic standard that some traditions would reject. A tradition may value truth, liberation, union, or obedience more than visible social function. Re-entry also varies by lineage: a forest renunciant, a householder, a monk, and a poet may show different fruits without one being less realized. The Daoist decreasing method helped prevent forced convergence, but it may also make doctrine look too fluid and underweight moral discipline. The model should be downgraded if close practice manuals show that re-entry criteria are secondary, inconsistent, or merely modern ethical projections.","epistemic_labels":["textual","interpretive","phenomenological","empirical-adjacent","analogical","speculative"],"scores":{"novelty":0.79,"generativity":0.87,"cross_tradition_support":0.68,"logical_coherence":0.84,"explanatory_compression":0.8,"empirical_adjacency":0.48,"practice_testability":0.72,"counterargument_quality":0.84,"source_reliability":0.64,"publishability":0.81},"next_research_directions":["Build a re-entry audit rubric with fields for ownerless action, reduced grasping, ethical fruit, relational humility, stability over time, and community or teacher verification.","Test the rubric on specific instructions for the Advaita jivanmukta, Buddhist no-attainment, Daoist wu wei, and Sufi recollection or adab.","Ask whether dual-trained practitioners report the same re-entry fruit after different peak or post-negation interpretations.","Protocol improvement: after using any contemplative method as a thinking lens, ask how the method returns to public claims, action, and accountability."]}
